The Crown's Weight
A Skyrim Campaign Session for 5 Players (Adept Tier)
Estimated Play Time: 6-8 hours (2 sessions recommended)
 Party Size: 5 players
 Difficulty: Scaled for Adept Tier (Party has 8 AP each)
 Reward: 1 Advancement Point (already awarded at end of Race for the Crown)

Adventure Summary
In the frozen aftermath of Korvanjund, the Skyrim Wardens stand victorious but battered. The dragon cult lieutenant Ulag the Breaker has escaped into the darkness, the Jagged Crown rests heavy in Kyboh's pack, and Galmar Stone-Fist waits with barely-contained hope for the party to honor their bond. But the victory is hollow. Davinia feels the Crown of the Pale Lady tightening its grip on her soul. Alfonso's plague ghouls lie scattered across the crypt floor. Kyboh's gloves smoke with arcane burnout. Saijah feels the psychic scream of a dying sacred tree hundreds of miles away. And Orion knows that Varon, the Dark Brotherhood enforcer hiding among the Stormcloaks, has decided Hroki can no longer be killed cleanly in this camp.
The party must now make the most important political decision of their lives: what to do with the Jagged Crown. Their choice will determine the course of the Civil War, their standing with the factions, and whether Galmar Stone-Fist—the man who treats Davinia like family—will become their greatest ally or their most personal enemy. And waiting in the wings, three crises burn across Skyrim, each demanding immediate action. They can save only one.
This is the weight of the crown. This is the cost of power.

PART I: THE AFTERMATH (THE SURFACE CAMP)
Setting
The siege camp outside Korvanjund, late afternoon. The snow has stopped falling, but the wind howls through the valley. Behind the party, the entrance to the ancient tomb has collapsed completely, sealed forever under thousands of tons of rock. The Stormcloak soldiers are celebrating—cheering, embracing, raising their weapons to the sky. The party stands in the center of the chaos, battered, bleeding, and alive.

Opening Beat: The Hero's Welcome (Told as Recap)
Read Aloud: "You stumbled out of Korvanjund into the blinding white of the Pale's afternoon sun, the freezing cold air hitting your lungs like a hammer after hours in the tomb's dust and death. Behind you, the mountain shuddered—a deep, grinding boom as the entrance collapsed in on itself, sealing the ancient stones forever under thousands of tons of rock.
The Stormcloak camp erupted in celebration. Soldiers ran toward you, their faces split with disbelief and joy. They'd seen you go in. They'd heard the collapse. They hadn't expected anyone to come out.
The cheering swelled into a roar: 'THEY MADE IT! THE LANTERNS DID IT!'
Galmar Stone-Fist strode with you through the snow, his armor dented and scorched, his shield reduced to a splintered wreck—but grinning with the fierce, savage joy of a man who just survived the impossible.
That was hours ago. Now the camp has settled into purposeful activity. You've reached your cart, where Old Bjorn waits with the smell of honey-mead and woodsmoke."
GM Note: This sets up the victory as past action, transitioning smoothly into the current camp scene where the session properly begins.

Beat 1: Bjorn's Welcome (The Kindly Grandpa)
Setup: The party approaches their cart. Old Bjorn is sitting on the driver's bench, and the smell of expensive honey and woodsmoke drifts from the campfire beside it.
Read Aloud: "You approach your cart, and the first thing that hits you is the smell—rich, sweet honey-mead and a crackling cookfire. Bjorn is sitting on the driver's bench in just a light tunic despite the Pale's freezing winds, sharing a bottle of Black-Briar Reserve with a young courier wearing the distinctive black-and-silver livery of Maven Black-Briar's house. The courier looks both star-struck and slightly tipsy.
Bjorn looks up as you approach, his weathered face breaking into a wide, toothy grin. He raises the bottle in salute.
'There they are! The Crown-Seekers! Come, sit. The stew's almost done, and this mead...'
He takes a swig and smacks his lips.
'...well, it isn't Honningbrew, but it'll wash the grave dust from your throats.'
He turns to the courier and pats the young man's shoulder with enough force to make him wobble.
'Go on then, lad. Tell Maven her specialists are alive and well. And tell her if she wants to impress them next time, she should send the Gold Label.'
The courier stammers a farewell and hurries off toward his horse, clutching a sealed letter confirming the party's survival."
Character Beat: The Unremorseful Partner
If any player questions Bjorn about drinking their advance payment, he simply chuckles and hands the remaining bottle to the party.
"This was advanced payment for the obsidian lanterns, we're the Lanterns aren't we? A man's got to stay hydrated to keep these horses in line. Besides—"
He gestures to the camp, to the celebrating Stormcloaks, to the sealed tomb behind them.
"—you lot just walked out of a mountain that tried to eat you. I figured we'd earned a drink on arrival."
If Asked About the Light Clothing:
If any player notices and asks why he's not freezing:
"The blood's just pumpin' better lately. Must be the excitement. You know how it is after a good fight—the body forgets it's supposed to be cold."
GM Note: This establishes several things:
Bjorn is now fully invested as "the Grandpa" of the Wardens.
The Black-Briar courier represents the Riften adventure hook—Maven is watching and waiting.
Bjorn is unfazed by the party's monstrous nature. He's seen worse in his War-Hound days.
The light tunic detail is the first subtle hint that Bjorn was struck by Sahloknir's soul at Kynesgrove and something fundamental has changed within him.

Beat 2: Galmar's Pitch (The Bond)
Setup: As the party settles around Bjorn's fire, Galmar approaches. He's been giving his men time to tend wounds and celebrate, but now he sees the Wardens gathered together in one place.
Read Aloud (Galmar's Dialogue): "Galmar approaches your group at the cart, his heavy boots crunching in the snow. He stops before you, and for a moment he just looks at Davinia, then at all of you, with something like wonder in his eyes.
Then he claps a heavy, gauntleted hand on Davinia's shoulder, his grip firm but reverent.
'By Ysmir, I haven't fought like that since the Great War. You lot... you fight like daedra. You fight like Nords.'
His gaze sweeps over the group, taking in each bloodied face, each weapon still sheathed, each body still standing when they should have fallen.
'Listen. We're done here, but the North is in trouble. Runners from the Pale came through this morning while we were in the tomb. Dawnstar has gone dark. The few who made it out before the city fell tell stories of the dead walking the walls. Organized, like what we saw in there.'
He looks back at Davinia, his voice dropping but losing none of its intensity.
'I don't know who—or what—is leading them, but it's like here. They have a leader. They're an army. And they've taken a city intact.'
He straightens, his hand still on her shoulder.
'I'm taking the First Cohort north to breach Dawnstar. But walls are just stone, and stone can be broken by siege engines and patience. What I need are warriors with experience. Who can walk into that nightmare and kill whatever's giving the orders.'
He looks at each of you in turn.
'Come with us. Fight beside me in the Pale. We take Dawnstar back, and we break the back of this dead army together. What do you say?'"
GM Note: This is an invitation, not an order. Galmar is offering them a place in history. He's offering brotherhood. This is the first of the three adventure hooks, delivered with genuine emotion before politics can complicate it. The choice is theirs.
Pacing: Allow the players to respond if they wish, but don't let this turn into a full debate yet. Galmar is making an offer—they don't need to answer immediately. The decision comes later, after all the information is on the table.

Beat 3: The Calm Before the Storm
Setup: Galmar returns to his command tent after making his pitch. The Stormcloaks are packing up siege equipment and preparing for the march north, but they're allowing a few hours for rest and celebration first. The party has a window of relative peace.
Read Aloud: "The camp settles into a purposeful bustle. Soldiers are breaking down tents, loading wagons, and tending to their wounded. Galmar is at the command tent, conferring with his officers over maps. Captain Hroki—promoted after holding the collapsing doorway—is being tended by medics, his new rank already changing how the other soldiers treat him. Respectful nods, offered water, careful hands on his injured shoulder.
Bjorn has a fire going beside your cart, and the smell of a thick, hearty stew begins to fill the air. He gestures to the logs he's arranged around the fire.
'Sit. Eat. You look like you've been chewed up by a troll and spit out the other side. I've got questions, and I imagine you've got a few of your own, but first—food.'"
GM Note: This is the transition into PART II: The Order of Business. The party has about 2-3 hours of in-game time before Galmar will approach them about the Jagged Crown. Use this time for individual character spotlights.
ROLL FOR ORDER OF BUSINESS HERE!
The players roll to determine spotlight order. The structure should feel like The Warden's Wake—individual, intense character moments interspersed with communal fire scenes and Bjorn's quiet wisdom.

PART II: THE ORDER OF BUSINESS (THE INDIVIDUAL SPOTLIGHTS)
GM Guidance: Running the Order of Business
This section is modeled directly on The Warden's Wake structure. Each character gets a private or semi-private moment to deal with the consequences of Korvanjund and the weight of their personal arcs. These scenes should be intense, personal, and mechanically significant.
The Initiative Order (for pacing):
Kyboh 12
Saijah - Varon's scene happens during one of these 4
Davinia 10
Alfonso (Ylva's confrontation happens during this) 8
Orion - Varon's scene happens during one of these 15
Key Rule: Varon's scene must work regardless of whether Orion or Saijah goes first. Structure it so it can slot into either position.

1. Kyboh: The Psychic Static
Context: Kyboh is sitting on a crate near the cart, away from the fire. He's staring at his hands. The Gloves of the Pugilist are fused to his skin, grey and ceramic-like, smoking faintly in the cold air. His Boots of the Comet hum with a low, dissonant vibration that only he can feel.
Setup: Ask another player to be present for this scene—someone sitting with Kyboh or approaching to check on him.
The Narrative:
Read Aloud: "You sit apart from the fire, your hands resting on your knees. The gloves feel heavier than they should. The grey calcification has spread slightly since the fight, creeping from the gloves onto the skin of your forearms—anyone looking closely can see it.
You try to flex your fingers. They move, but there's a stiffness now, a resistance that wasn't there before. It feels like trying to bend cold iron.
The Boots of the Comet vibrate against your feet, a rhythmic pulse synced against your heartbeat. It's like wearing two competing metronomes that are somehow beating in time with each other."
The Symptom: The Loop of Personality
GM Prompt (Narrative Intrusion):
As Kyboh processes this, have him make a casual observation or joke to the player next to him. When he does, interrupt:
"You start to say something—a joke, an observation, something to break the tension—but the moment the words leave your mouth, you hear them again. An echo. Your own voice, slightly delayed, bouncing around inside your skull.
It's louder than the original. Funnier, somehow. More clever. You're so distracted by how good your own wit sounds that you completely lose track of what the other person is saying in response. Their mouth is moving, but all you can hear is your own voice, looping, repeating, drowning everything else out.
When the echo finally fades, they're staring at you, waiting for a response. You have no idea what they just said."
Mechanical Effect: Kyboh's -2 Guile penalty is now actively narrated as cognitive disruption. He is becoming "hollow"—his own personality is echoing back at him before he can process external input.
The Physical Escalation: The Creaking Joints
Read Aloud: "You shift your weight, and your knee makes a sound. Not the normal pop of cracking joints—this is a deep, grinding creak, like the sound of a ship's hull under pressure.
You look down. The skin around your knees is slightly grey, the same texture as the gloves. The calcification is spreading."
Mechanical Warning:
If Kyboh uses his Boots of the Comet ability or a high-impact attack in the next combat, inform him that he feels his radius bone creaking under the strain. He risks taking an expanded crit fail window: each time he rolls a crit fail while using the boots, his crit fail threshold increases by 1, so now a 20 or 19 is a crit fail and so on.
If Kyboh Discusses This With the Other Player:
Let him explain what he knows about Hjolmar Ice-Shaper and the Maker's Forge. Kyboh has this information—he's researched it, been told about it multiple times, and he's even told Bjorn about it.
The other player can offer sympathy, advice, or encouragement, but the weight of the decision (go to Winterhold immediately vs. help with the crisis) is his alone.
Bjorn's Intervention (If Kyboh Approaches Him):
If Kyboh seeks Bjorn's advice, Bjorn can only offer what Kyboh has already told him.
Bjorn's Dialogue: "Bjorn looks at the smoking gloves and nods slowly.
'The forge you mentioned. North of Winterhold, past the College, up in the ice fields. That smith you told me about—Hjolmar Ice-Shaper.'
He meets your eyes.
'You know more about this than I do, lad. You've done the research. You know where to go and what needs fixing. The question isn't whether you can fix it. The question is whether you will. Before it's too late.'"
GM Note: Bjorn does NOT have independent knowledge of Hjolmar. He only knows what Kyboh told him. This advice reflects that—Bjorn is holding up a mirror, not providing new information.

2A. Orion: The Silver Leash (If Orion Goes Before Saijah)
Context: Orion is checking his gear near the cart, away from the main celebration. He's adjusting the Ring of the Pale Regent on his finger, feeling the cold weight of Valerius's surveillance. Across the camp, Captain Hroki is visible, surrounded by well-wishers, now a war hero and effectively untouchable.
The Narrative:
Read Aloud: "You slip away from the fire to check your gear. Your fingers instinctively go to the ring on your hand—the Ring of the Pale Regent, heavy and cold despite the hours you've worn it.
As you adjust it, you feel the now-familiar sensation: a phantom weight on your mind, a sense of being observed. Valerius is listening. He's always listening.
You glance across the camp. Hroki is there, laughing despite the pain of his injured shoulder. Soldiers clasp his hand. Medics fuss over him. He's a hero now. Protected. Galmar's personal appointment to Captain of the City Guard.
The Brotherhood wanted him dead three sessions ago. And you've done nothing."
The Arrival: Varon (The Professional Assessment)
Read Aloud: "A familiar voice speaks from behind you, low and cultured.
'Orion.'
You turn. It's Varon—the surgically modified Bosmer pretending to be a Breton. You've seen through his disguise: the too-rigid ears, the reshaped features. He's been hiding among the Stormcloaks since before Korvanjund, blending in seamlessly with his false face.
He's the one who gave you the Hroki contract in the first place, back when Hroki was just a guilt-ridden sergeant. Now Hroki is a war hero.
Varon stands there in his Stormcloak gear, utterly unremarkable to everyone else in camp. His expression is neutral, professional.
'A moment of your time. Privately.'"
The Meeting: The Revised Plan
Varon doesn't waste time with pleasantries. He's here to deliver a professional assessment of the changing situation.
Varon's Dialogue: "He gestures to a quieter spot away from the main camp. Once you're alone, he speaks quietly.
'The situation has changed. Look at him.'
He nods toward Hroki across the camp.
'Three sessions ago, he was a sergeant. Guilty. Isolated. An easy mark. Now he's Captain Hroki, war hero, personal appointee of Galmar Stone-Fist. He's surrounded by loyal veterans. He's a symbol.'
Varon's tone remains clinical, matter-of-fact.
'Killing him here would be... messy. The Stormcloaks would turn on you. Your party would be forced to fight their way out or face execution. The Brotherhood doesn't waste useful assets on theatrical failures.'
He meets your eyes.
'The contract stands. But the method must change. Hroki will travel to Windhelm to assume his new post within the week. He'll be vulnerable on the road, or in the city before his security detail is fully established.'
A pause.
'I will accompany you. To ensure the contract is fulfilled correctly this time. When the moment is right, in Windhelm, we will complete the work together.'
His tone makes it clear this isn't a request or a negotiation. It's a professional adjustment to circumstances.
'Do you understand?'"
GM Note: Varon is NOT threatening to kill Orion directly. The threat is implicit in the word "accompany"—Varon is now Orion's shadow, his watcher, ensuring the job gets done. Varon becomes a traveling NPC, a constant presence reminding Orion of his unfinished contract.
The Valerius Complication (The Counter-Order):
As Varon finishes speaking, the Ring of the Pale Regent burns ice-cold on Orion's finger.
Read Aloud: "The moment Varon finishes speaking, the ring flares with vibration, the base of your skull starts to pulse with pain. Not the gentle, observing cold you've grown used to—this is urgent, commanding.
A voice echoes in your mind.
'The Brotherhood's leash tightens. Predictable. But Hroki is the key to the Bear's heart. Do not kill him yet. He is leverage. Galmar trusts him. Galmar trusts Davinia. Through Hroki, I can manipulate the Stormcloak line when I need it.'
The pain intensifies.
'You will ensure Hroki survives. The assassin must be... managed. Misled. Delayed. When I need Hroki dead, I will tell you. Until then, he lives. Do you understand, Orion?'
The voice fades, but the pain lingers."
The Crossroads:
Orion is now caught between:
The Brotherhood (Varon): The contract will be fulfilled in Windhelm, with Varon watching.
Valerius (The Ring): Keep Hroki alive as leverage over Galmar.
The Party: Hroki is a friend of the Wardens. Killing him would prove Krusp Fanck right.
Varon's Departure:
"Varon nods, as if the matter is settled.
'Take me to your cart driver and party and introduce me as an ally.'
He waits for you to take him but something tells you he already knows the way."
GM Note: This is Orion's Tier 3 Crossroads moment. Varon is now a traveling NPC. The pressure cooker is live, but the timeline has extended to Windhelm. Let the player sit with this weight.

2B. Orion: The Silver Leash (If Saijah Goes Before Orion)
Context: Same setup—Orion is checking his gear. But Varon has already spoken with Saijah and is now approaching Orion directly.
The Arrival: Varon (The Professional Assessment)
Read Aloud: "A familiar voice speaks from behind you.
'Orion. A word.'
You turn to see Varon—the surgically modified Bosmer hiding as a Breton among the Stormcloaks. You've seen through his disguise before: the reshaped features, the false face. He's been with the camp since before Korvanjund, completely invisible to the Stormcloaks around him.
He's the one who gave you the Hroki contract in the first place. Now he's here about that unfinished business.
His expression is neutral, professional.
'I just finished speaking with Saijah. Fascinating woman. But I'm here about our mutual business.'"
The Meeting: The Revised Plan
The dialogue proceeds identically to 2A—Varon explains that killing Hroki in camp is no longer viable, proposes Windhelm as the new location, and announces he'll be accompanying Orion to ensure the contract is fulfilled.
The Valerius counter-order also proceeds identically.
GM Note: The order doesn't matter—Varon's message to Orion is the same. The only difference is whether he's already spoken with Saijah or is about to.

3A. Saijah: The Psychic Migraine (If Saijah Goes Before Orion)
Context: Saijah is standing away from the fire, facing southeast. Her head is pounding. Ever since Korvanjund, the psychic scream she felt from the Eldergleam has become a constant, low-level migraine. It's not debilitating, but it's persistent—a reminder that something sacred is dying and she wasn't there to stop it.
The Narrative:
Read Aloud: "You stand at the edge of the camp, looking toward the horizon. Southeast. Toward Eastmarch. Toward the Eldergleam Sanctuary.
The migraine pulses behind your eyes, rhythmic and relentless. It's not pain, exactly—it's wrongness. Like listening to a song played on broken strings. The land itself is out of tune, and you can hear it.
You close your eyes and reach out with your Greensight, trying to find the pulse of the Green. Instead, you feel only the absence. A hole where something vast and ancient used to sing.
The Eldergleam is still alive, but it's dying. And it's screaming."
The Arrival: Varon (Clan Recognition)
Read Aloud: "Footsteps approach from behind. You turn to see Varon, the surgically modified Bosmer hiding among the Stormcloaks as a Breton. You saw through his disguise when you recognized the clan signs—the way he moved, the words he chose. You both speak Jel. You both came from the same shadowscale satellite clan. You acknowledged each other briefly with a look, but you've never actually spoken.
He stands there in his Stormcloak gear, hands clasped, his posture respectful.
'Saijah,' he says quietly. 'Vena.'
The term isn't 'sister.' It's more intimate than that—acknowledging respect, but also... interest.
He gestures beside you, where you've been staring southeast.
'May I?'"
The Conversation: The Opening
Varon steps beside you, then notices your posture—the tension, the pain.
Varon's Dialogue: "'We never spoke. Back when we recognized each other. Clan signs, the language.'
Pause.
'Something's wrong. I can see it in how you're standing.'
He looks southeast with you, then back.
'What is it?'"
GM Note: Let Saijah respond. She can tell him about the Eldergleam, the corruption, the psychic migraine—or she can deflect. This is her choice to share or not. Once she explains (if she does), THEN Varon can make his pitch about handling the violent part (killing cultists) while she handles the healing part.
If Saijah Explains:
Varon listens, his expression focused, clinical.
Varon's Response: "'A sacred tree. Corruption from a source.'
He's quiet for a moment, thinking.
'Cut out the source, the tree heals itself. The people doing this—they're the problem, not the tree.'
He looks at her, noting the hawk circlet.
'You're trying to heal it. I can see that. But if the people poisoning it are still there...'
Pause.
'Let me handle them. You focus on the tree. We both do what we're good at.'"
The Romantic Undertone (Subtle):
If Saijah engages with his offer rather than immediately rejecting it, Varon is quiet for a moment.
Varon's Dialogue: "'I used to feel it too. The Green. When I was younger, before the work became everything.'
A pause.
'You walked away from the clan. I stayed. You kept something.'
He looks at her directly.
'I miss it sometimes.'
He uses 'Vena' again.
'Think about it, Vena.'"
GM Note: Varon and Saijah are from the same shadowscale satellite clan. They recognized each other through clan signs and Jel, but never spoke beyond that acknowledgment. This is their first real conversation. Varon can see she's in pain, staring southeast. He can see the hawk circlet but doesn't necessarily know it represents Kynareth. He sees she walked away from the clan—chose something else over the blade. He's drawn to her precisely because she represents a connection to "the Green" (nature, life, growth) that he sacrificed. He uses "Vena" (a term meaning something like "blooming" or "worthy one") instead of "sister" because his interest is romantic, not familial. This is the beginning of his pursuit—he wants to prove his way is necessary, but he also genuinely admires what she's become and wants to be near someone who still has what he gave up.
The Transition:
Varon steps back.
"'I need to talk to Orion. Think about it, Vena.'
He walks toward where Orion is checking his gear."
