5. Alfonso: The Tactical Assessment (And Ylva's Confrontation)
Context: Alfonso is sitting near the edge of camp, away from the fire. The ghouls he created inside Korvanjund—sixteen of them, made by corrupting the meat the soul gems were using to construct more draugr—are gone. Destroyed in the collapse or burned by Ulag's venting steam. He registers the loss tactically: sixteen mobile shields, sixteen vectors for infection, sixteen distractions. He'll need to rebuild.
The Narrative:
Read Aloud: "You sit on a supply crate, eyes half-closed, assessing. The sixteen ghouls you created in Korvanjund—built from corrupted draugr-meat, animated through your synthesis—are gone. Destroyed.
You catalogue the loss: sixteen mobile shields, sixteen infection vectors, sixteen tactical assets. You'll need to rebuild the next time you find suitable material.
But the work itself went well. The corruption took hold efficiently. The animation was stable. The synthesis of Namira and Peryite is improving."
The Arrival: Ylva (The Confrontation)
Read Aloud: "Heavy footsteps approach. You look up to see Ylva striding toward you, her jaw set, her movements purposeful. She's not angry—anger is hot, explosive. This is something colder. Disappointed. Like a teacher who expected better.
She stops directly in front of you and drives the haft of her massive battleaxe into the frozen ground between you with enough force to crack it. Chips of ice scatter.
She looks down at you.
'We need to talk, Rot-Elf.'"
GM Note: Ylva has been simmering with frustration since Korvanjund. She joined the party for the "Great Hunt," but Alfonso's mass-ghoul strategy robbed her of the chance to fight Ulag directly. She didn't land a single meaningful blow. She's in a state of Burning Indignation.
The Confrontation: Using Others to Fight Your Battles
Ylva's Dialogue: "'Your thralls. Your walking dead.'
She gestures vaguely toward where the tomb entrance used to be.
'You stood in that tomb and threw sixteen corpses between you and the Orc. Sixteen meat shields. I didn't get to fight. I didn't get to hunt. I just stood there and watched your minions die for you.'
She leans in.
'You're using others to fight your battles. That's not fighting. That's hiding.'
She pulls back and crosses her arms.
'I joined you because I thought you were a predator. A hunter. But you're sending others to do it for you while you stand back and watch.'"
The Biltong Observation (The Compliment Wrapped in Critique):
Ylva steps closer, sniffing Alfonso deliberately. Her nose wrinkles, but there's a gleam of interest in her eyes.
Ylva's Dialogue: "'You smell better now, though. I'll give you that.'
She inhales, considering.
'Before, you smelled like aging meat. Ripe. Ready to collapse. But now you smell like biltong. Cured. Salted. Hard. Like a hunt that's been properly preserved.'
She meets his eyes.
'But you're still not hunting. You're still hiding behind your thralls. And I'm done watching.'"
The Ultimatum:
Ylva's Dialogue: "'Here's how this works now, Rot-Elf: Your thralls can flush prey, drive them toward us, panic them. But when there's a real fight—a worthy target—YOU fight. Not your corpses. You.'
She pulls her axe from the ground.
'I get first blood on worthy prey. And YOU stand beside me and fight like you mean it. Your thralls clean up trash. They don't fight your battles for you. Understood?'"
The Choice:
Alfonso must decide:
Option A: Accept the Deal He promises to fight directly on worthy targets. His ghouls become support, not primary combatants.
Immediate Effect:
Ylva stays with the party.
She's still angry with him. No more kissing. No more sleeping together.
If Alfonso makes a particularly compelling promise about how he'll fight alongside her, she might reward him by sleeping with him once to seal the deal.
In future combats, Alfonso must engage worthy targets directly. Ylva gets narrative priority on bosses/elites.
Option B: Refuse the Deal He tells Ylva his tactics are his own. She can accept them or not.
Immediate Effect:
Ylva stays with the party but she's furious.
No kissing. No sleeping together. She's cold toward him.
She will actively avoid being near him in combat.
The relationship is damaged, possibly permanently.
Option C: The Middle Path (Negotiate) He offers a compromise: He'll fight directly on targets Ylva identifies as "worthy," but retains full control over ghoul tactics in large-scale fights.
Immediate Effect:
Ylva accepts grudgingly. "Fine."
She's mad at him now but will come around once he proves it.
No immediate intimacy, but the door isn't closed.
She will test this arrangement in the next combat.
GM Note: Ylva's problem isn't with traps or tools—it's with using others (thralls, summons) to fight your battles. She wants to see Alfonso fight directly, not hide behind animated corpses. She doesn't leave the party regardless of his choice, but the relationship consequences vary significantly. 

