PART V: THE STINGERS
The Valerius Letter
Setup: As the party finishes loading the cart and preparing to leave, a nondescript figure approaches. He's not a soldier, not a courier—just a traveler in dark, nondescript clothing. He moves through the camp without anyone stopping him, like he belongs everywhere and nowhere.
He stops in front of Davinia and holds out a sealed letter.
Read Aloud: "The man doesn't speak. He simply places the letter in your hand, nods once, and walks away, disappearing into the camp before anyone can question him.
The letter is sealed with dark wax—no crest, no marking. The envelope itself is made of expensive vellum, but there's something wrong about it. It's too smooth, too perfect.
You break the seal.
The letter inside is written in dried blood."

The Letter
Read Aloud (Davinia): "To Davinia of the Caelinus branch,
I have read the reports from the road. The Imperial Tax Collectors. Brutal work. Efficient.
I have secured the evidence in my private archive. It would be a tragedy for the General to learn that his daughter has stained his impeccably polished reputation with common murder.
I see the Caelus blood. It demands power.
We are of the same root, cousin. Come to Solitude when you are ready to stop playing soldier. We have a dynasty to discuss.
— Lord Valerius Caelus"

The Effect
Read Aloud: "The letter feels cold in your hand. Not metaphorically—physically cold, like it's been stored in ice.
The implications crash over you like a wave:
He knows about the tax collectors. He has evidence—enough to destroy your father's career, to have you arrested for murder. But he's not turning you in. He's keeping you out of jail so he can use you later.
And he called you 'cousin.' Not metaphorically. He's claiming blood relation. The ancient Caelus line, the one your father came from before the name was changed to Caelinus. Valerius is the Ancient Root. Your father is the Cadet Branch.
He's blackmailing you. He's claiming you. And he's watching."
GM Note: This is a major revelation. Davinia now knows:
She's being blackmailed by a vampire lord.
Valerius is family—her cousin, from the original bloodline.
He has leverage over her, over the party, and over her father.
Solitude is no longer a safe haven. It's a trap waiting to spring.

The Shambling Remnant
Setup: As the party is preparing to depart the camp, just as they're about to leave, movement at the tree line catches their attention.
Read Aloud: "As you finish loading the cart and prepare to depart, movement at the edge of camp draws your attention. A figure stumbles out of the tree line.
It's a ghoul. A plague ghoul. Alfonso's plague ghoul.
This one is water-logged, its flesh grey and bloated like a corpse pulled from a river. Its clothing is tattered, soaked, covered in mud and dead leaves. It moves with the jerky, uncoordinated gait of something that's been walking for days without rest, navigating by instinct alone.
It stops at the edge of the firelight and turns its head toward Alfonso. Its eyes are milky white, but there's recognition there. It knows him. It's been looking for him.
A Stormcloak sentry shouts in alarm: 'UNDEAD! SOMETHING'S COMING IN!'"
The Complication: The Stormcloak Reaction
Read Aloud: "Soldiers scramble for weapons. If Galmar is still in camp, his head snaps up. Ylva's hand goes to her axe, her eyes lighting up with the prospect of a fight.
The ghoul doesn't care. It walks through the camp like it's the only thing in the world, guided by the psychic thrum of Alfonso's connection. It stops in front of him, standing there, waiting for orders."
The Explanation:
If Galmar is still present (Scenarios A or C), he strides over.
Galmar's Response: "Galmar stares at the ghoul, then at Alfonso, his jaw tight.
'So this is yours. Another one of your walking dead.'
He doesn't draw his weapon, but his hand stays near it.
'I've seen worse. I've fought beside worse. Just keep it on a leash. And if it attacks one of my men, I'll put it down. Understood?'"
If Galmar is gone (Scenarios B or D), the remaining Stormcloaks give Alfonso and his ghoul a wide berth, muttering prayers to Arkay.
The Omen:
The ghoul's arrival serves as a reminder to the party—and any watching Stormcloaks—that Alfonso's work is self-sustaining. His ghouls don't just die when destroyed. They seek him out, crossing miles of wilderness, guided by his connection to Peryite and Namira.
Alfonso's Response:
Let Alfonso handle this however he wishes. He can command the ghoul to follow, dismiss it, or use it as needed. It's a tool, and he registers it as such.
GM Note: This is the very last beat before departure. The shambling remnant is a reminder of Alfonso's power and the price of that power.

CONCLUSION: THE PATH CHOSEN
The Closing Narration
Read Aloud: "The decision is made. The arguments are settled. The bloody letter feels cold in Davinia's pocket. Orion's ring hums with Valerius's cold surveillance. Alfonso's ghoul stands in the shadows, waiting. Kyboh's gloves smoke. Saijah's migraine pulses. Varon watches from somewhere in the camp, patient and inevitable.
The Jagged Crown sits in someone's pack, a weight of history and treason.
Three fires burn across Skyrim. You've chosen which one to face. The others you will leave to fate.
As the last of the Stormcloaks settle for the night—or march north, depending on your choice—Bjorn finishes loading the cart. He climbs onto the driver's bench and takes up the reins.
'Mount up. We leave at first light.'
Dawn breaks over the Pale. The road is open. Your path is chosen.
We end the session here."

